18.821 | Project Laboratory in Mathematics | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/mathematics/18-821-project-laboratory-in-mathematics-spring-2013 | level:Undergraduate features:Selected video lectures, Special feature - video, Projects and examples, Instructor insights, This Course at MIT prereq:two mathematics subjects numbered 18.100 or above instructors:Fall: H. R. Miller Spring: H. Cohn term:U (Fall, Spring) description:Guided research in mathematics, employing the scientific method. Students confront puzzling and complex mathematical situations, through the acquisition of data by computer, pencil and paper, or physical experimentation, and attempt to explain them mathematically. Students choose three projects from a large collection of options. Each project results in a laboratory report subject to revision; oral presentation on one or two projects. Projects drawn from many areas, including dynamical systems, number theory, algebra, fluid mechanics, asymptotic analysis, knot theory, and probability.  3-6-3 units. Institute LAB
